{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"44bc151b-72c1-4d10-a5c5-1de0e8426f4b","content":"The project isn't in this workspace, but here's what you need. Create or edit `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your server must use **stdio transport** (not HTTP/SSE). If using the `ModelContextProtocol` NuGet package, configure it with `.WithStdioServerTransport()`.\n- The `--project` path is relative to the workspace root.\n- For a **published** build, swap the command to `\"command\": \"dotnet\", \"args\": [\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]` instead.\n\nAfter saving, open the Copilot chat panel in **Agent mode** — it will auto-discover and start the server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"d892372f-4a14-49b3-a428-900d566e590d","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The project doesn't exist yet. That's fine — the user said they built it. I just need to give them the `mcp.json` configuration. Let me provide the correct configuration for using a C# MCP server with VS Code agent mode via stdio transport.","outputTokens":343,"requestId":"5035:C31CE:D6E70A:F6E0EC:69F2AB3F"},"id":"5298e527-a096-4dbe-9c7f-4e950d98a32e","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:07:19.927Z","parentId":"3b1eb50b-5f6b-4a9b-99c1-cc8ba78ed1a5"}
